    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1965-11-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1965-11-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="107"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d107">
                <head>107. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_KRW2" type="from">Robert W.
                        Komer</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to the President’s
                    Special Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_BMG2"
                        type="to">Bundy</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d107fn1"
                        >Source: Johnson Library, National Security File, Country File, Iran, Vol.
                        I, Cables, 1/64–12/65. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1965-11-22">November 22, 1965</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Mac:</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Iran interest rate on arms sales</hi>. I’ve held this up for
                    over 8 weeks now, in order to keep it tied to Peshawar package. But we’re going
                    nowhere fast, and heat is mounting (see Tehran 743 attached).<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d107fn2">
                        <ref target="#d106">Document 106</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Case for holding up has been that giving away a goodie too long before we ask for
                    something in turn vitiates the leverage. But State and <gloss target="#t_DOD1"
                        >DOD</gloss> think the Shah would still remember, and also argue the case
                    for going ahead now anyway on general grounds of keeping Iranians happy. Also
                    Iran is talking about purchasing arms elsewhere at cost to our balance of
                    payments. Past rate has been 5%. State/<gloss target="#t_DOD1">DOD</gloss> want
                    to cut it <pb facs="0217" n="189" xml:id="pg_189"/> to 3–1/2–4% (ultimately
                    about $350 million in sales over next several years may be involved).</p>
                <p>Other problem is that <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName> wants to
                    lay off this paper with Ex-Im, thus freeing <gloss target="#t_MAP1">MAP</gloss>
                    credit fund for other sales. It will take a WH whip, of course, to get Linder to
                    do this.</p>
                <p>I favor going ahead now at 4%, so long as I have your backing in beating up
                        <persName>Harold</persName> when necessary.<note n="3" xml:id="d107fn3">Next
                        to this paragraph <persName corresp="#p_BMG2">Bundy</persName> wrote “OK”
                        with his initials.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">RWK</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
